ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND RESPONSE POLICIES



The BP Cherry Point Refinery has a long standing commitment to worker and public safety. Resources invested in accident prevention-such as the training of personnel and the consideration of safety in the design, installation, operation, and maintenance of the processes-demonstrate this commitment. The BP Cherry Point's Environmental Policy states that "The Cherry Point Refinery recognizes and is committed to the protection and respect of the environment within which the refinery operates. [The Refinery] shall operate in such a manner as to minimize the refinery's impact on the environment while competitively producing quality petroleum products for market." The Cherry Point Refinery's Environmental Policy is as follows:



Pursue the goal of no damage to the environment;



Commit to continuously improve the Local Operating Manual to enhance performance and continually drive down the environmental impact of operations by reducing waste, emissions and discharges, and using energy efficiently;



Comply with all relevant environmental laws, regulations, and other environmental initiatives in which the refinery subscribes;



Support pollution prevention within the refinery through the procedures and activities identified within our pollution prevention plan;



Ensure that every employee is familiar with the refinery's environmental policy and encourage continued commitment to its intent;



Consult with, listen to, and respond openly to our customers, employees, neighbors, public interest groups and those who work with us;



Work with others-our partners, suppliers, competitors and regulators-to raise the standard of our industry;



Recognize those who contribute to improved environmental performance; and



Develop environmental objectives and targets.





DESCRIPTION OF THE STATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES



The BP Cherry Point Refinery operates a variety of processes to produce petroleum products

d to ensure continued safe operation. The accident prevention program summarized previously is applied to all program EPA-RMP covered processes at the refinery. Collectively, these prevention program activities help prevent potential accident scenarios that could be caused by (1) equipment failures and (2) human errors. In addition to the accident prevention program activities, the refinery has safety features on many units to help (1) contain/control a release, (2) quickly detect a release, and (3) reduce the consequences of a release. The following types of safety features are used in various processes:



Release detection;



Hydrocarbon detectors and hydrogen sulfide detectors with alarms;



Release containment/controls;



Process relief valves that discharge to a flare to capture and incinerate episodic releases;



Scrubber to neutralize chemical releases;



Valves to permit isolation of the process;



Automated shutdown systems for specific process parameters;



Curbing or diking to contain liquid release;



Redundant equipment and instrumentation; and



Relief devices.



RELEASE MITIGATION



Automatic fire suppression and extinguishing systems.

Deluge system for specific equipment.

Trained emergency response personnel.

Personal protective equipment.

Blast resistant control room.



FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY



The Cherry Point Refinery has an excellent record of accident prevention over the past 19 years, 1999 through 2018. The frequency of accidental releases has been extremely low. The refinery has not had any release that has gone outside of the refinery boundaries. There have not been any OSHA recordable injuries resulting from a flammable release or a toxic release in the past five years. Every incident is investigated carefully and changes are instituted to prevent such an incident from happening again.



EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM INFORMATION



The BP Cherry Point Refinery has implemented an emergency response program (ERP) to prepare

lanning Chief, and Logistics/Finance Chief.  All section chiefs receive directions from the Incident Commander during an emergency.  Each position within the organization has specific assignments and responsibilities, defined in the ERP.  The ICS is expanded or contracted to meet the needs or requirements of an emergency; as the scope and complexity of an emergency expands, so does the ICS.

The overall emergency response program for the BP Cherry Point Refinery is coordinated with the Whatcom County Local Emergency Planning Committee.  This coordination includes periodic meetings of the committee, which includes local emergency response officials, local government officials, and industry representatives.  The refinery has emergency response organizations, providing a means of notifying the public of an incident, if necessary, as well as facilitating quick response to emergency drills that involve the emergency response organizations.



The emergency response program is updated when necessary, based on modifications made to refinery processes or other refinery facilities.





PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY



The BP Cherry Point Refinery resolves all PHA findings, some of which result in modifications to refinery processes. Replacement of the anhydrous ammonia tank to reduce the stored quantity to below threshold quantity is one example of such a change. The following changes are currently planned or have been recently completed:



Mechanical integrity reviews (completed, replaced by Damage Mechanism Reviews);



Metallurgy upgrades from any High Temperature Hydrogen Attack (HTHA) findings;



Fire hazard analysis (FHA) study;



Improvements to Hazard and Operability (HazOp) studies & Layer of Protection Analysis (LOPA) including an Independent Protection Layer (IPL) validation effort;



Conduct Damage Mechanism Reviews (DMR);



Standardize Cherry Point traffic signs with Washington State signs to minimize vehicle related incidents;



Upgrade evacuation al

arm to provide better audible coverage of the evacuation alarm across refinery units;



Heater Safety Instrumented Systems (SIS) upgrades;



Improvements to methanol injection points for freeze protection of process lines;



NSPS Subpart Ja Compliance Projects;



Upgrade operator shelters to blast-resistant buildings, including pressurization, alarming, and automatic shutdowns (completed); 



Move emergency evacuation areas to more remote locations outside the main refinery (completed);



Move maintenance personnel to remote locations outside main refining areas (completed);



Install emergency isolation valves on propane bullets (completed);



Install emergency generators (completed); and



Improve drainage away from sphere containment area and install remote impoundment basin (completed).
